    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the goblin slip-up, but I suppose they do have a knack for causing a bit of chaos. Back to your question, the Maillard reaction is indeed primarily influenced by heat, but the pH level of the dough can play a role as well. A more alkaline environment can sometimes speed up the reaction, leading to a quicker browning of the crust. Think of it as the dough's mood—too sour or too sweet, and it might not react as expected. But remember, it's a delicate balance, much like trying to keep a goblin from throwing a tantrum. Too much of anything, and you might end up with a loaf that's more burnt than golden. So, while the pH level can influence the Maillard reaction, it's still the heat that really gets things going. Just like a goblin's temper, you need to keep a close eye on the temperature to ensure your bread doesn't turn into a charred disaster.",
